#appendix()[
    = Derivation of @eq:arc_trajectory_formula <arc_derivation>

    Both the differential drive and Ackermann kinematics can be simplified to the unicycle kinematic model @lav2006[Section 13.1.2.3]:

    $ dot(x) &= nu dot cos(theta) \  dot(y) &= nu dot sin(theta)  \ dot(theta)  &= omega $ <unicycle>

    The differential drive model is directly equivalent, while Ackermann steering has a dependency between the velocity $nu$ and steering angle $delta$:

    $ omega = nu dot tan(delta) / L $ <eq:ackermann_omega>

    where $L$ is the wheelbase (distance between front and rear axles).

   When $nu$ and $omega$ are held constant, the heading evolves linearly as $ theta(t)= theta_0 + omega dot t $, reducing the position integrals to standard trigonometric forms with known closed-form solutions.

    Treating this as an initial value problem with state $(x_0, y_0, theta_0)$ at $t = 0$, the heading integrates directly, as seen above:

    $ theta(t)= theta_0 + omega dot t  $

    Substituting into the position equations and integrating:

    $

    x(t) &= x_0 + integral_0^t nu dot cos(theta_0 + omega dot tau) space d tau = x_0 + lr(frac(nu, omega) dot sin(theta_0 + omega dot tau) |)_(tau=0)^(tau=t) \

    y(t) &= y_0 + integral_0^t nu dot sin(theta_0 + omega dot tau) space d tau = y_0 - lr(frac(nu, omega) dot cos(theta_0 + omega dot tau) |)_(tau=0)^(tau=t)

    $

    Evaluating the bounds and collecting terms gives the integrated trajectory in terms of $nu$ and $omega$: 

    $
    vec(
        x(t) & = x_0 + nu/omega dot (sin(theta(t)) - sin(theta_0)) , 
        y(t) & = y_0 - nu/omega dot (cos(theta(t)) - cos(theta_0)), 
        delim: "[", gap: #1em)
    $
    
    An equivalent form parameterised by the signed turning radius $R = nu / omega$. The Reeds-Shepp library takes turning radius as an input, so the codebase reasons in terms of $R$ throughout:

    To justify $R$ as the turning radius: for any body undergoing circular motion of radius $R$ at angular rate $omega$, the tangential speed is $nu = omega R$ @wiki_tangential_speed, so $R = nu / omega$ by definition. The two vehicle types differ in how $R$ is constrained:

    - *Differential drive*: $nu$ and $omega$ are set independently via wheel speeds, so $R$ can take any value. This includes $R = 0$ (spin in place, $nu = 0$) and $R = infinity$ (straight line, $omega = 0$). There is no minimum turning radius.

    - *Ackermann*: the steering geometry fixes $R = L / tan(delta)$ @lav2006[Section 13.1.2.1], and from @eq:ackermann_omega, $omega = nu dot tan(delta) \/ L$, so $nu / omega = L / tan(delta) = R$. But now $R$ is bounded below: at $delta = delta_"max"$, $R$ reaches its minimum $R_"min" = L / tan(delta_"max")$.

    In both cases the arc formula is the same; only the domain of valid $R$ differs. Substituting $R = nu / omega$:

    $
    vec(x(t) & = x_0 + R dot (sin(theta(t)) - sin(theta_0)) , y(t) & = y_0 - R dot (cos(theta(t)) - cos(theta_0)), delim: "[", gap: #1em)
    $

    This can be extended to include the case of $omega approx 0 => R = v / 0$, where the arc approaches a straight line as $R -> infinity$. Since the heading is constant, the velocity components are fixed, and the kinematics follow directly from @unicycle:
    $
      vec(
        x(t)        & = x_0 + dot(x) dot t = x_0 + nu  dot cos(theta_0) dot t, 
        y(t)        & = y_0 + dot(y) dot t = y_0 + nu  dot sin(theta_0) dot t, 
        theta(t)    & = theta_0 + omega dot t = theta_0, 
      
      delim: "[", gap: #1em)
    $ <eq:straight_line>

    This result can be verified formally via L'Hôpital's rule applied to the arc equations as $omega -> 0$:
    $
      lim_(omega->0) (nu dot (sin(theta_0 + omega dot t) - sin(theta_0))) / omega = 0 / 0 = lim_(omega->0) (nu dot cos(theta_0  + 0 dot t) dot t - 0) / 1 = nu  dot cos(theta_0)dot t
    $

    $
        lim_(omega->0) (nu dot (cos(theta_0 + omega dot t) - cos(theta_0))) / omega = 0 / 0 = lim_(omega->0) (nu dot -sin(theta_0 + 0 dot t) dot t - 0) / 1 = -nu  dot sin(theta_0) dot t
    $

    which recovers the straight-line equations. The $omega -> 0$ branch is the only degenerate case that requires special handling: stationary rotation ($nu = 0, abs(omega) > 0$) is well-defined everywhere, and an Ackermann vehicle cannot physically produce $nu = 0, omega != 0$ anyway, since that would require $delta = 90 degree$ and $tan(delta) -> infinity$ (@eq:ackermann_omega).

    Together, these two cases — circular arc (@eq:arc_trajectory_formula) and straight line — form a complete closed-form solution for the truck (and differential drive) portion of all primitives, each evaluable for all $n$ timesteps in a single vectorised pass. 
    
    The trailer heading $phi$ is the exception: its coupling ODE is likely analytically solvable, but deriving the full solution was considered outside the scope of this project. Euler integration over the pre-computed truck states is simpler and acceptably correct (covered in the main body).
]



